[[Lieutenant-General]] '''Sir Edward Peter Strickland''' [[Order of the Bath|KCB]] [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]] [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]] [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]] (3 August 1869 - 24 June 1951) was a [[British Army]] officer who commanded [[1st Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|1st Infantry Division]] during [[World War I]].

==Military career==
Educated at [[Warwick School]],<ref name=odnb>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/98119 Peter Strickland at Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]</ref> Strickland was [[Commissioned officer|commissioned]] into the [[Royal Norfolk Regiment|Norfolk Regiment]] in 1888 and served in Upper [[Burma]] in 1888/1889, on the Dongola expedition in 1896<ref name=lh>[http://www.kcl.ac.uk/lhcma/locreg/STRICKLAND.shtml Liddell Hart Centre for Military Archives]</ref> and fighting at the [[Battle of Atbara]] and the [[Battle of Omdurman]] in 1898.<ref name=odnb/> He served in North [[Nigeria]] from 1906 and commanded the North Nigeria Regiment in 1909.<ref name=lh/> He served in [[World War I]] as Commanding Officer of 1st Bn the [[Manchester Regiment]] from 1914 and as Commander of the Jullundur brigade from early 1915 leading it at the [[Battle of Neuve Chapelle]] and at the [[Second Battle of Ypres]].<ref name=odnb/> He continued his war service as Commander of the 98th Brigade from late 1915 and then as [[General Officer Commanding]] [[1st Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|1st Infantry Division]] on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] from 1916 until the end of the War leading it at the [[Battle of the Somme]] and the [[Battle of the Lys (1918)|Battle of Lys]].<ref name=lh/>

After the War he became Commander of the Western Division of the [[British Army of the Rhine]]<ref name=odnb/> and then General Officer Commanding [[6th Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|6th Division]] in [[Ireland]]<ref name=lh/> in which role he survived an [[assassination]] attempt by the [[Irish Republican Army]] in [[Cork (city)|Cork]] in September 1920 before assuming the additional responsibilities of military governor for the counties of [[Munster]], [[County Kilkenny|Kilkenny]] and [[County Wexford|Wexford]] in January 1921.<ref name=odnb/> He was appointed General Officer Commanding [[2nd Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|2nd Division]] in 1923 and General Officer Commanding the [[Egypt Command|British Troops in Egypt]] in 1927 before retiring in 1931.<ref name=lh/>

==Family==
In 1918 he married Barbara Cresswell (née Ffolkes); they had a daughter, and there were two daughters from his wife's previous marriage. Barbara Strickland was created a [[Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (DBE) in 1923.<ref name=odnb/>

==Honours==
* '''DSO''': [[Distinguished Service Order]] - ''1899''
* '''CMG''': [[Order of St Michael and St George|Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]] - ''1913''
* '''KCB''': [[Knight Companion of the Order of the Bath]] (Companion (CB) ''1917'')
* '''KBE''': [[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]
*{{flagicon|Ottoman Empire}} Third class, [[Order of Medjidie]] - ''1902'' - in recognition of valuable services rendered to Hs Highness the Khedive of Egypt<ref>{{LondonGazette| issue=27415 |supp= |startpage=1727 |date=11 March 1902}}</ref>

